 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'TheSavior', 'comment_id': 628835333.0, 'datetime': '2020-05-14 19:14:02+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_2', 'text': "| Type       | Required |
| ---------- | -------- |
| React.Node | No       |

The type of React.Node in the table isn't quite right since it can also take a function. Perhaps it should be something like this for both `children` and `style`?

`React.Node | (PressState) => React.Node`


----------
Also, since we can't embed a Snack for the example since Snack won't have this version, could it have an animated gif instead?", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'TheSavior', 'comment_id': 628872909.0, 'datetime': '2020-05-14 20:35:18+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_2', 'text': "Also, I think the image across the top that shows the order of events might not be quite right. press and longPress will never both fire for the same event. onPress fires after longPress, but before onPress. I feel like articulating these complexities and ordering might be out of scope for the documentation and make it more complicated than not including it. What do you think?

Also I highly recommend checking out the examples in RNTester to validate the content here. See this recording of the press events example that showed me that the image isn't quite right.

![android_Phone_Screen_Recording_2020-05-14_at_12 18 40](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/249164/81982904-5d171800-95e7-11ea-9b92-d2138db85306.gif)", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'rachelnabors', 'comment_id': 629225450.0, 'datetime': '2020-05-15 13:07:07+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_1', 'text': "Thanks for all your feedback, @Eli, and for clarifying how the interactions work. I actually had trouble running RNTester until last night, thus had to work with source and tests to make this illustration. I do feel the illustration helps explain the sequence of events. Changing the diagram to reflect that is not impossible :)

I agree, the 130ms can go as people might set timers by it. But the 500ms should probably stay as it's the default.

As for `RectOrSize`, perhaps it should live on its own Object Type page as well, given that many learners are unfamiliar with both flow notation and TS notation.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'rachelnabors', 'comment_id': 629261733.0, 'datetime': '2020-05-15 14:19:05+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_1', 'text': '@username_2 Almost forgot! Re Android-at-the top: all props are alphabetized now. It would be weird to put iOS and Android out of order. Perhaps we could shift them to a "Platform Props" section further down the page. Thoughts, @username_3?', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'Simek', 'comment_id': 629454665.0, 'datetime': '2020-05-15 20:00:52+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_3', 'text': 'I just have pushed the initial version of the `PressEvent`. All the descriptions are based on the things I was able to deduce from the code and playing with live events. Probably not all of the them will be 100% accurate. Keys with missing description: `changedTouches`, `target` and `touches`. Hope someone with better knowledge about events and event system can correct me and fill the gaps in.

Also from the test I have made it looks for me that `force` should be marked as an option field/key in the `CoreEventTypes` definition: https://github.com/facebook/react-native/blob/master/Libraries/Types/CoreEventTypes.js#L91', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'rachelnabors', 'comment_id': 630312866.0, 'datetime': '2020-05-18 16:59:22+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_1', 'text': "![shera_feels-powerful](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/236306/82239631-fbc9ae80-9930-11ea-9422-8162a24eae75.gif)

And that's a wrap, folks! Thanks @username_3 for working on the label, attribute and design updates! Thanks to @username_0 for writing the doc! And thanks to @username_2 for providing technical direction and feedback! (And a special thanks to @yungsters for helping me figure out the sequence of events to make that illustration 100% accurate!)

Great work, everyone! This sets a new standard for how we document components and APIs :)", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}]

